<HEADLINE>
'TAIWAN NIGHT' HELD AT BERLIN FILM FESTIVAL
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Berlin, Feb. 13 (CNA) 02/13/07  14:43:51 (By Lin Yu-li and Steve
Bercic)
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's Government Information Office held a "Taiwan Night"
cocktail reception here Monday evening as part of the ongoing
57th Berlin Film Festival, with nearly 200 foreign media and
movie industry representatives attending the event.
</P>
<P>
Also on hand at the cocktail party, held at the Hotel Marriot in
the German capital, were the directors of the locally-produced
films "Mei" and "Spider Lilies, " as well as several actors and
actresses starring in the films.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the cocktail reception, Taiwan's representative to
Germany, Shieh Jhy-wey, who hosted the event, introduced the
Taiwan guests and expressed the hope that everyone could
encourage and support the new generation of Taiwan directors and
actors by checking out their movies.
</P>
<P>
After the cocktail party, portions of director Arvin Chen's
"Mei", which has been selected to participate for Best Short Film
in the Short Film Competition of the festival, and Zero Chou's
"Spider Lilies, " which has been included in the Panorama section
of the festival,  were screened  for the guests  and received
their enthusiastic applause.
</P>
<P>
During the cocktail party, the Taiwan filmmakers engaged in
friendly exchanges with their foreign counterparts as well as
organizers of several major international film festivals.
</P>
<P>
This marked the first time that the GIO has held a "Taiwan Night"
cocktail reception at the Berlin Film Festival. The move was part
of the GIO's efforts to help local filmmakers expand into
overseas markets.
</P>
